<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="161" type="">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="161">
The holotypes of both oblongus and striatus are in NHML. They have been directly compared, and I consider that they represent a single species, with minor variation in the density of the vestiture. I have also examined a series collected by Dr. B. Valentine in Kenya, and compared them with the holotype of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Hapalogenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hapalogenius oblongus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="161" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oblongus">Hapalogenius oblongus</taxonomicName>
. The species is recorded from Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania, and from the host tree genera: 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Acacia" order="Fabales" pageId="4" pageNumber="161" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Acacia</taxonomicName>
(Leguminosae), 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Croton" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Croton" order="Malpighiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="161" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Croton</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName genus="Euphorbiaceae" lsidName="Euphorbiaceae" pageId="4" pageNumber="161" rank="genus">Euphorbiaceae</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eucalyptus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucalyptus" order="Myrtales" pageId="4" pageNumber="161" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Eucalyptus</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName genus="Myrtaceae" lsidName="Myrtaceae" pageId="4" pageNumber="161" rank="genus">Myrtaceae</taxonomicName>
). This suggests that it is a polyphagous species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
